data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc` with native-sized integers.** Both `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>` work:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[5];
```

This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint` and `nuint` were introduced as first-class types (aliases for `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr`). They're unmanaged types, so they satisfy the `stackalloc` constraint. On this 64-bit machine each element is 8 bytes; on a 32-bit runtime they'd be 4.
